<A NAME = "5"></A>Copyright
TR DAILY via NewsNet
January 2, 1996

MARYLAND PSC SETS INTERCONNECTION, RESALE RATES

The Maryland Public Service Commission has set the rates and
conditions for interconnection and other aspects of local
exchange competition in the state.  The commission established
standard rates for terminating local traffic and the terms for
local competitors to resell Bell Atlantic-Maryland's local
service.  The PSC also adopted an interim number portability plan
and granted competitors the flexibility either to establish new
local calling areas or to use those of Bell Atlantic. 
Additionally, the commission required all carriers to provide
"911" service and launched a separate proceeding to examine
universal service issues.  The PSC in 1994 authorized MFS
Intelnet, Inc., to be the first provider of competitive local
service in the state (TR, May 2, 1994 and Aug. 8, 1994).  It
since has authorized MCImetro and TCG America, Inc., to enter the
local exchange services market.  TCG today endorsed the
commission order.  Later this month the PSC is scheduled to
consider an application by AT&T Corp. to provide both business
and residential local service (TR, Dec. 25, 1995).



